<h3>Invitation:</h3>
You are invited to take part in a research project. Before you decide whether or not you would like to participate it is important that you read the information provided below. This will help you to understand why and how the research is being carried out and what participation will involve. Please let the researcher who gave you this information know if anything is unclear or you have any questions. Thank you for your time.
<h4>Who is conducting the research?</h4>
This study is being undertaken by 4th year Student Cameron Taylor within the Discipline of Computing, University of Dundee.
<h4>Who is funding the research?</h4>
This is non-funded research as part of an undergraduate degree project.
<h4>What is the purpose of the research?</h4>
The purpose of this research is to explore Fitts’ Law and Mobile Devices. The aim of the study is to improve the user experience when using mobile devices.
<h4>Why have I been invited to take part?</h4>
You have been invited to take part to assess the potential of using this system and evaluate its effectiveness. 
<h4>Do I have to take part?</h4>
No. Taking part is voluntary, choosing not to take part will not disadvantage you or the study in any way. You may decide to withdraw from the study at any time without explanation and without penalty. If you decide to withdraw from the study then any data or information collected from you up to that point in time will be removed and destroyed. Even if you don’t withdraw from the study you do not have to answer all questions or complete all tasks that are presented to you. 
<h4>What will happen if I take part?</h4>
By taking part in this study you will be asked to take part in a Fitts’ Law type task and interviewed about your mobile application habits and asked how it relates to the task you have completed.
<h4>Are there any risks in taking part?</h4>
There are no expected risks.
<h4>Will my taking part in this project be kept confidential?</h4>
The data collected will not contain any personal information about you. We will follow ethical and legal practice and all information about you will be handled in confidence.
It will not be possible to link publicly the data you provided to your identity and name. You will be given a participant ID which shall be anonymised and not linked to you in any way (e.g., P01) and any information about you regarding age or gender shall be kept separate from any identifying information about you except your anonymised ID which will not be linked to you in any way. 
All digital data and documents containing (or linking to) the original identification of the participants will be stored securely on the encrypted University’s Box file storage system, only accessible to the named researchers.  
<h4>What will happen to the information I provide?</h4>
All digital data and documents containing (or linking to) the original identification of the participants will be stored securely on the encrypted University’s Box file storage system, only accessible to the named researchers.  
We will keep the consent forms and data in separate folders. The specific data recorded will only be accessible to the named researchers and will be destroyed on completion of the project. The anonymised results of the study may be used in future publications and incorporated into databases to inform future professional practice.
The results of this study will be presented as anonymised data or anonymous quotes from which participants cannot be identified. By request to the researchers the results of the study may be accessed by participants.
<h4>Data Protection</h4>
No personal data will be collected other than general demographics, e.g. such as your age group, your level of experience in using the type of system that you are presented with to evaluate, and general preferences you may have for the usage of such a system or the type of data that it contains.
The University asserts that it lawful for it to process your personal data in this project as the processing is necessary for the performance of a task carried out in the public interest or in the exercise of official authority vested in the controller.
The University of Dundee is the data controller for the personal and/or special categories of personal data processed in this project.
The University respects your rights and preferences in relation to your data and if you wish to update, access, erase, or limit the use of your information, please let us know by emailing cutaylor@dundee.ac.uk. Please note that some of your rights may be limited where personal data is processed for research, but we are happy to discuss that with you. If you wish to complain about the use of your information please contact the University’s Data Protection Officer in the first instance (email: dataprotection@dundee.ac.uk). You may also wish to contact the Information Commissioner’s Office (<a href = https://ico.org.uk/> https://ico.org.uk/</a>).
You can find more information about the ways that personal data is used at the University at: <a href= https://www.dundee.ac.uk/information-governance/dataprotection/ >https://www.dundee.ac.uk/information-governance/dataprotection/</a>. 
<h4>Is there someone else I can complain to?</h4>
If you wish to complain about the way the research has been conducted please contact the Convener of the University Research Ethics Committee (<a href= https://www.dundee.ac.uk/research/ethics/contacts/ >https://www.dundee.ac.uk/research/ethics/contacts/</a>).
<h4>Alternative formats</h4>
If you require a copy of the Participant Information Sheet and Consent Form in an alternative format (e.g. large print, Braille) then please notify the principle researcher who is conducting the evaluation with you.
